The  expected results of this directive are as follows:


  Real property is managed in a manner that enables  operational outcomes, demonstrates sound stewardship and provides best value, consistent  with the Government of Canadaâs socio-economic and environmental objectives;
  Real property decisions are based on risk  management practices, performance information and an assessment of full  life-cycle costs;
  Effective governance and oversight  mechanisms are in place to support the management of real property; 
  Opportunities for collaboration are  considered in real property decisions; 
  Workforce capacity for real property  management is developed and maintained commensurate with organizational need; 
  Transactions related to real property are fair,  open and transparent, and demonstrate due diligence; and
  Acknowledging the relationship between Indigenous  peoples and the land, real property management decisions contribute to  reconciliation with Indigenous peoples.

The senior designated official(s) for the  management of real property in a custodian department is responsible for the  following:



    Establishing, implementing and maintaining a  department-wide real property management framework consisting of  processes, systems and controls that:


      Include oversight, planning and  reporting mechanisms;
      Incorporate performance results and  lessons learned to inform real property decision-making; 

        Include an information system that:


          Enables the collection and generation  of comprehensive and accurate data on real property holdings, operations and  transactions;
          Enables year-over-year comparison; 
          Is linked to departmental financial  information systems and processes;
          Enables the development and  maintenance of a portfolio-level decarbonization plan; and
          Supports government-wide reporting  requirements;



        Contribute the real property  perspective to departmental planning functions, including ensuring that the  real property portfolio strategy inputs to the departmentâs investment plan are  in accordance with the 

          Policy on the  Planning and Management of Investments

        , AppendixÂ A: Mandatory  Procedures for Investment Plans; and

      Facilitate collaboration between  real property officials and program leads to enable informed and integrated  real property management decisions;



    Providing advice to the deputy head on: 


      The nature, structure and  resourcing of the departmentâs real property management function;
      Significant gaps in  performance and issues of non-compliance with the requirements of this  directive;
      The departmentâs real property  portfolio strategy;
      Investments required to maintain  the integrity of the departmentâs real property portfolio and to optimize its  operational efficiency, environmental performance and climate resiliency; and

        Seeking the necessary Treasury  Board approvals when the value of a transaction will exceed the 
        Transaction  Approval Limits and Conditions for the Acquisition or Disposition of Real  Property
        ;



  Identifying and managing the departmentâs  needs with respect to the necessary competencies, capacity, and professional  development in real property management;
  Ensuring the development, implementation and  monitoring of a real property portfolio strategy;
  Cultivating relationships with Indigenous  peoples on matters related to real property;

    Ensuring that real property transactions are  conducted in a manner that:


      Is fair, 
      Aligns with commercial real estate  practices, 
      Respects treaties and other  agreements between the Crown and Indigenous peoples, and 
      Includes an open solicitation of  offers unless the minister is satisfied that the nature of the transaction  would make an open solicitation of offers inappropriate or not in the  public interest;


  Ensuring compliance with appropriate  building codes, fire codes and applicable specialized standards;
  Investigating serious fires, in cooperation  with local authorities, and ensuring that resulting recommendations are  addressed; and

    Certifying annually to the Treasury Board of  Canada Secretariat the completeness and accuracy of the information submitted  to the:



        Directory of  Federal Real Property
        ;


        Federal  Contaminated Sites Inventory
        ; and


        Government of  Canadaâs Greenhouse Gas Emissions Inventory
        .

Real property practitioners in a  custodian department are responsible for the following:









      Engagement with Indigenous peoples



    Engaging Indigenous peoples on matters  related to real property to fulfill duties and obligations of the Crown, and  respond to interests as appropriate;







      Planning and governance



    Supporting the senior designated real  property official(s) in establishing, implementing and maintaining the real  property management framework;
    Operating and maintaining a real property  information system;
    Monitoring the functionality, utilization, and  physical, environmental and financial performance of real property assets over  their life-cycle;
    Developing the real property portfolio  strategy;







      Stewardship and use



    Maintaining the physical performance and  functionality of real property;

      Supporting the optimization of the real property  portfolio by identifying real property that is underutilized, inefficient or no  longer needed for departmental programs in order to: 


        Better utilize the property in the  context of the real property portfolio strategy;
        Dispose of surplus real property; or
        Manage surplus real property  that cannot be disposed of in a way that reduces costs while minimizing Crown  liability;


    Identifying opportunities to share special-purpose  real property by assessing the costs and benefits of co-locating with other  federal departments, other levels of government, and other organizations that  have complementary objectives;

      Charging the following in co-occupation and  lease-out situations:


        Costs of occupation, on a prorated  basis, to other federal departments, other levels of government, and public  institutions, such as universities, that co-occupy special-purpose real  property, in order to advance or support complementary objectives; or
        Market rent in all other situations  where a party occupies underutilized federal real property that is still needed  for program purposes; 


    Having occupancy, lease or licence agreements  that set out the roles and responsibilities of the parties involved; 
    Ensuring  that parties not subject to this directive that occupy federal real property do  not impede the delivery of federal programs and departmental compliance with  the requirements of this directive;
    Consulting  with the Department of Justice Canada, Indigenous Services Canada, and Crown-Indigenous  Relations and Northern Affairs Canada when the Crown contemplates a change in  use of real property;
    Consulting with Indigenous peoples when there is a legal duty to consult about an intent to dispose of real property;

      Notifying official language minority communities of the intent to dispose of real property and, in accordance with theÂ 

        Official Languages Act

      , consulting with English or French linguistic minority communities and other stakeholders, including school boards or commissions, in the province or territory where the federal real property or federal immovable is located;

    Considering  opportunities to co-own, co-manage, or share the use of real property with  Indigenous groups, recovering costs as and where appropriate;

      Limiting the negative environmental impact of  real property in a way that is consistent with the governmentâs sustainable  development objectives, including reducing or avoiding to the degree possible:


        Waste production;
        Resource and energy use;
        Greenhouse gas emissions; and
        Site contamination;


    Taking immediate and reasonable action to  mitigate risk to human health and to the environment in the event of  contamination, before assessing a future course of action;

      Managing contaminated sites by: 


        In Canada, following standards and  guidelines endorsed by the Canadian Council of Ministers of the Environment, or  their equivalents;Â 
        Outside of Canada, complying with  applicable environmental legislation or regulations and, where none exist,  adopting appropriate Canadian best practices to minimize the impacts of contamination; 
        Assessing suspected and known  contaminated sites to determine the most appropriate, sustainable, and  cost-effective action; 
        Prioritizing remediation or risk  management activities on sites that pose the highest risk to human health and the  environment; and
        Undertaking site remediation or risk management  to the extent required for current or intended federal use, unless the  department can demonstrate that more stringent remediation would represent best  value to the federal government;



      Implementing  the commitments set out in the 
      Greening Government Strategy
      ;

    Considering diversity, including gender  identity and gender expression, in the design and provision of built amenities;
    Conserving the heritage value of federal heritage  properties in Canada by following the procedures set out in AppendixÂ A:  Mandatory Procedures for Heritage Assessment and Conservation; Â 
    Conducting appraisals and estimates following AppendixÂ B:  Mandatory Procedures for Appraisals and Estimates;
    Providing barrier-free access to federal real  property as prescribed in AppendixÂ D: Standard on Barrier-Free Access to  Real Property;







      Transactions



    Conducting due diligence before acquiring, disposing, or transferring administration of real property as prescribed in Appendix E: Standard on Due Diligence







      Acquisition



    Validating the need for acquiring real property  based on program needs and on the real property portfolio strategy; 
    Undertaking a full life-cycle analysis, before  acquiring a real property asset or interest, to seek best value;
    Justifying the amount paid for transfers of  administration from agent Crown corporations, transfers of administration and  control, and purchases of real property, including any goods and services  acquired through these transactions, in relation to market value as set out in AppendixÂ B:  Mandatory Procedures for Appraisals and Estimates; 







      Disposal



    Disclosing the results of due diligence measures  to prospective purchasers, where   appropriate;
    Consulting with the Department of Justice  Canada, Indigenous Services Canada, and Crown-Indigenous Relations and Northern  Affairs Canada when the Crown contemplates a disposal of real property by way  of sale, exchange, gift, easement, transfer of administration, or transfer of  administration and control;
    Notifying CLC of the intent to dispose of real property;

      Consulting  with Canada Lands Company CLC Limited (CLC) to identify surplus real property  for potential sale to CLC when any of the following criteria may apply:


        The size of the property or the value  of the sale could negatively affect markets if it is not appropriately managed; 
        There is an opportunity to add value through redevelopment;
        Partnerships with other organizations  could be the best mechanism to increase benefits to the government and to  Canadians; or 
        Sensitive policy issues exist;


    Collecting  expressions of public purpose interest in all or a portion of the site  simultaneously from federal departments, agent Crown corporations, provinces, municipalities,  and Indigenous groups; 
    Providing CLC the opportunity to acquire properties identified under subsectionÂ 4.2.31;
    Obtaining confirmation from CLC that it has been engaged but elected not to acquire a site that meets any of the criteria in subsection 4.2.31;

      Granting priority to acquire for public purpose, properties that do not meet the criteria identified in subsection 4.2.31, or sites CLC has elected not to acquire, in the following order: 


        federal departments; 
        agent Crown corporations;
        provinces; 
         municipalities and Indigenous groups; 


    Ensuring that identified public purpose interests, and an expectation to reasonably address them where feasible, are  included in agreements with CLC;
    Developing a business case for the disposal of surplus real property, supported by the valuation that was determined in accordance with Appendix B: Mandatory Procedures for Appraisals and Estimates;

      Mitigating  the risk associated with the disposal of sites containing contamination by any  of the following:


        Remediating the sites or taking  action to manage the risks associated with the contamination before disposing of  the sites;
        Requiring that the acquiring party remediate  the site after disposal; 
        Ensuring the legal transfer of  environmental liability to the acquiring party;


    Transferring  administration of real property to other federal departments and exchanging funds at a value to be agreed upon  between the departments, but no greater than the market value determined according  to the procedures set out in AppendixÂ B: Mandatory Procedures for Appraisals  and Estimates;
    Justifying  the amount paid for transfers of administration to agent Crown corporations,  transfers of administration and control, and sales of real property, in  relation to market value according to the procedures set out in AppendixÂ B:  Mandatory Procedures for Appraisals and Estimates; and







      Reporting



    Ensuring that information is reported in  accordance with Appendix C: Mandatory Procedures for Reporting.

Real property practitioners must apply the  mandatory procedures described below.



    Seek  a heritage evaluation of any building 50Â years of age or older from the  Federal Heritage Review Office at Parks Canada when the  building is:


      Crown-owned; or
       Planned for acquisition by purchase;


  Consult with the Federal Heritage Review Office at Parks Canada before undertaking any intervention that may impact the heritage value of a federal heritage property or an archaeological site on federal land, to ensure that appropriate heritage conservation advice is obtained;
  Consult with the Federal Heritage Review Office at Parks Canada before deciding to decommission, dispose (including lease-out), or demolish a federal heritage property or its components, to ensure that best efforts are made to conserve the heritage value of the federal heritage property.

Real property practitioners must apply the  mandatory procedures described below.



    Obtain at least one appraisal from  the Chief Appraiser of Canada before acquiring or disposing of real property,  except:


      When there will be an open solicitation of offers  and the total value of the real property interest is anticipated to be less  than $500,000; in this situation, obtain at least one current estimate of the  market value; 
      When there is no open solicitation of offers and the  value of the lease or licence is anticipated to be less than $25,000 total  consideration; in this situation, obtain at least one current estimate of the  market value; 
      When there is a transfer of administration between federal departments at a value less than or equal to net book value, no appraisal or estimate of the market value is required;


  Segregate transaction and valuation  responsibilities related to real property transactions.

Real property practitioners, except for those  in custodian departments that have been excluded from full reporting by  decision of the Executive Director of the Investment Management Directorate, Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat, must apply the mandatory  procedures described below.









      Reporting  information for inclusion in the Directory of Federal Real Property (DFRP) and  the Federal Contaminated Sites Inventory (FCSI)



    Inform the Treasury Board of Canada  Secretariat of designated officials, including the authorized official,  official contact, financial contact (where applicable), and data submitters for  the DFRP and FCSI;
    Input reports to the DFRP and FCSI as  prescribed in the applicable input guides;
    Provide new or revised information,  with the exception of the data specified in subsectionÂ C.2.2.4, for  inclusion in the DFRP and FCSI within 90Â days of a change, including  acquisition, disposal, amendment to an existing record, or change in the  organizationâs contacts;
    Report annual expenditure, liability  and site performance data to the FCSI at fiscal year-end;
    Support the annual certification of  the completeness and accuracy of organizational records and contacts in the  DFRP and FCSI as prescribed in the applicable input guides;
    Reconcile all DFRP and FCSI records  and applicable fields with internal real property and building management systems,  contaminated site management systems, and financial systems;
    Reconcile FCSI annual financial  records with the financial statements submitted for the Public Accounts of  Canada;







      Reporting  to the Centre for Greening Government




      Inform the Centre for Greening Government of  designated officials, including the authorized official, official contact, and  data submitters for the 
      Government of Canadaâs Greenhouse Gas Emissions  Inventory
      ;


      Provide required data for inclusion  in the Government of Canadaâs Greenhouse Gas Emissions Inventory in accordance  with the annual call letter, the 

        Federal Greenhouse Gas Accounting and Reporting Guidance

      , and other applicable input guides;


      Support the annual certification of the  completeness and accuracy of organizational data submitted in accordance with  the 

        Federal Greenhouse Gas Accounting  and Reporting Guidance

       and other applicable input guides.

Real property practitioners must apply this standard  as described below.



    Ensure that where amenities are  provided on federal real property they are accessible and barrierÂ free and:



        If in Canada, they follow the Canadian Standards AssociationâsÂ 

          Accessible Design for the Built EnvironmentÂ 
          (CAN/ASC B651)

        , co-branded by CSA Group and Accessibility Standards Canada; and

      If outside of Canada, they align with  the requirements of the local jurisdiction;


  Ensure that an accessible route from  the main entrance is provided to accessible parking spaces, local public transit  stops and all drop-off areas that are located within the limits of federal real  property;
  Equip  classrooms, auditoriums, meeting rooms and theatres of more than 100Â square  metres with an assistive listening system encompassing the entire seating area;
  Provide signage and audiovisual  indicators for wayfinding and security;

Real property practitioners must do the  following in relation to exceptions and minor variations when applying this  standard.


  Establish internal  procedures for identifying and seeking deputy head approval of exceptions from  the accessibility requirements of this standard;
  Permit  minor variations from the requirements, on a case-by-case basis, if consistent  with the general intent of this standard, as long as the overall accessibility  is maintained; 

    Where  the accessibility requirements of this standard will significantly reduce the  heritage quality of the real property, some deviation is permitted; however,  the following must be ensured: 


      Access  to at least the main level of the building;
      Where  washroom facilities are inaccessible, equivalent facilities that are accessible  shall be provided; 


  Reassess  exceptions to ensure that they are still justified when initial criteria for  the exceptions change; and
  Document  rationale and maintain records of all approved exceptions and minor variations.
